            {
               "text": "### Images from Ashmolean\n\nThese images are copyright for Ashmolean and allowed to be used according to the license determined by them.\n\nTo visualize all images, use the left and right arrows on the slide below.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 4</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgEA\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgEA', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Excerpt of the epic of <i>Enmerkar and the Lord of Aratta</i>. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<htcite0>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Sumerians - Dynasties of Uruk: This section explores several Mesopotamian epics, including the Epic of Gilgamesh, which exerted a profound influence on cultural beliefs and narratives, many of which remain alive to this day (<htcite4>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">2 / 4</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgHarappaW\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHarappaW', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Harappa seal. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<htcite1>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Cradles of civilization (Part II): We continue the study by addressing the civilizations of Egypt, the Indus Valley, and China (<htcite14>)</li><li>Writing: Much more than an everyday tool, writing is a milestone that allows us to divide human history between prehistory and recorded history (<htcite5>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">3 / 4</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgS\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgS', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Statuettes of the sixth dynasty. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<htcite2>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>How big is the impact of the flood? First, it is necessary to determine when it supposedly would have occurred. Considering that one of the characters, Gilgamesh, was a historical king, it is possible to estimate the period in which he lived and compare it with other locations in the world at the time. Clearly, we observe that neither Egypt nor Peru were affected by the events described in Tablet XI of what we now know as the Epic of Gilgamesh (<htcite6>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">4 / 4</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"imgKL\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgKL', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Sumerian King List. © Ashmolean Museum, University of Oxford (<htcite3>).</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Sumerians - The Mythological Kings: Eight kings from the Sumerian King List, considered rulers before the Flood (<htcite15>).</li><li>Sumerians - Dynasties of Uruk: This section explores several Mesopotamian epics, including the Epic of Gilgamesh, which exerted a profound influence on cultural beliefs and narratives, many of which remain alive to this day (<htcite12>)</li><li>Sumerians - First Dynasty of Ur: We explore the first dynasty of Ur, present in the Sumerian King List, and how it relates to the Torah (<htcite18>).</li><li>Sumerians - Dynasties of Kish: Although many figures from this dynasty lack archaeological evidence, two kings have historical confirmation (<htcite13>).</li><li>Sumerians - Dynasties of Kish: Although many figures from this dynasty lack archaeological evidence, two kings have historical confirmation (<htcite19>).</li><li>Elamites - Awan Dynasty: One list mentions three kings who ruled for 356 years (Sumerian King List). Another list presents twelve kings who reigned for about 200 years (Awan King List). Why does this discrepancy exist? (<htcite17>)</li><li>Cradles of civilization (Part I): While humanity originated in Africa, the first civilizations emerged in various regions around the world, such as Mesopotamia, the Andes, and Mesoamerica (<htcite7>)</li><li>Sumerian King List: This text gathers all references to the Sumerian king list available in History Tracers (<htcite8>)</li><li>What is time?: In this text, we begin to explore one of the most important measurements in history and physics: time (<htcite9>)</li><li>Writing: Much more than an everyday tool, writing is a milestone that allows us to divide human history between prehistory and recorded history (<htcite16>)</li><li>Fractioning texts - In this text, we deepen the concept of groups and introduce fractions as an additional tool for text interpretation (<htcite10>)</li><li>How big is the impact of the flood? First, it is necessary to determine when it supposedly would have occurred. Considering that one of the characters, Gilgamesh, was a historical king, it is possible to estimate the period in which he lived and compare it with other locations in the world at the time. Clearly, we observe that neither Egypt nor Peru were affected by the events described in Tablet XI of what we now know as the Epic of Gilgamesh (<htcite20>)</li><li>Texts with Sciences (Part I): In the initial texts, we analyzed the relationship between texts and various sciences, although we have not yet performed a complete textual interpretation. In this text, we begin the exploration of ancient Mesopotamian texts, using the support of scientific studies. (<htcite11>)</li><li>Sources used in research: Text explaining the types of sources used in History Tracers (<htcite21>).</li></ul></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
